The original report is here: https://answers.atlassian.com/questions/38050627/answers/38059120

When a review contains a deleted (not published draft?) comment, closing it fails with NPE:

{noformat}
"URL: /json/cru/CR-608/changeStateAjax
A java.lang.NullPointerException was encountered
{noformat}

On big FRXs (tested on FRX with 2500 lines) scroll experience sucks. It can be faster, like on changeset page.
The problem sit in static/2static/script/cru/crucible-ui.js `movePage` method - it uses `transform` css rule to make header sticky. Changeset page uses `scrollTop`.
So the next change improves the scrolling experience a lot:

{code:javascript}
var movePage = function (position) {
  elements.page.scrollTop = position;
};
{code}


{code}
body#reviewpage #page {
    position: fixed;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100vh;    // add this
    overflow: hidden; // add this
    min-width: inherit;
}
{code}

However there is a side effect when AUI message displayed at the top of the page and the page is scrolled down a bit. This side effect currently can be observed on changeset page.
 !image-2016-01-27-11-06-48-546.png|thumbnail!

Users running FishEye/Crucible 4.0.0 or 4.0.1 with MS SQL Server will encounter the following error, when trying to perform a backup:
{code}
2016-03-21 10:25:19,952 WARN  - Backup failed.
java.io.IOException: Error reading database: Cannot encode value for unsupported column type: "bit" (-7) of column .cru_fisheye_user
	at com.atlassian.crucible.migration.item.SQLBackup$SaverImpl.backup(SQLBackup.java:82) [fisheye.jar:?]
	at com.atlassian.crucible.migration.BackupManagerImpl.createBackup(BackupManagerImpl.java:264) [fisheye.jar:?]
	at com.atlassian.crucible.migration.BackupManagerImpl.access$000(BackupManagerImpl.java:55) [fisheye.jar:?]
	at com.atlassian.crucible.migration.BackupManagerImpl$2$1.perform(BackupManagerImpl.java:153) [fisheye.jar:?]
	at com.atlassian.crucible.migration.BackupManagerImpl$2$1.perform(BackupManagerImpl.java:151) [fisheye.jar:?]
{code}

This does not affect users who upgraded directly to 4.0.2, and didn't ever run 4.0.0 or 4.0.1.

Note, scheduled backups would not finish too, admins may not notice.


h2. Workaround

Users can do the following to manually fix the functionality:

# Shutdown FishEye/Crucible
# Execute the following SQL script on the MS SQL Server database:
{code}
DROP INDEX cru_idx_perm_fisheye_user ON cru_global_permission;
ALTER TABLE cru_global_permission ALTER COLUMN cru_fisheye_user TINYINT NOT NULL;
CREATE INDEX cru_idx_perm_fisheye_user ON cru_global_permission (cru_fisheye_user);

DROP INDEX cru_idx_perm_crucible_user ON cru_global_permission;
ALTER TABLE cru_global_permission ALTER COLUMN cru_crucible_user TINYINT NOT NULL;
CREATE INDEX cru_idx_perm_crucible_user ON cru_global_permission (cru_crucible_user);
{code}
# Restart FishEye/Crucible

This can be logged when deleting a review.

{code}
org.hibernate.hql.internal.ast.HqlSqlWalker noClassMethodInfo - [DEPRECATION] Encountered positional parameter near line 1, column 67.  Positional parameter are considered deprecated; use named parameters or JPA-style positional parameters instead.
{code}

The message itself is harmless.

We should set "Store Diff" to false by default for Crucible-only instance, but then allow to turn it on. Currently its value is ignored:
{code}
if (crucibleOnly) {
    features.setStoreDiffs(false);
}
{code}

That leads to issues like [CRC-9326|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/CRC-9326] - when we have to hit SVN to retrieve blame info, which takes minutes.

Browser & Version: Chrome 49.0.2623.87
Crucible version: 3.8.0 Build:20150427140019 2015-04-27
Location: When viewing the changes for a document in a review (see attached image)
Steps to reproduce:
 - Create a new review
 - Add the attached patch file to the review
 - Select 'merchant 1-1.txt' document
 - Scroll up and down
 - Notice Jankiness
 -- Jankiness is more pronounced with changes of similar size against an actual repository where user, rev# and other data is also shown.  

Scrolling through documents in crucible is painful.  Especially so when the review contains many sources, or the source has many changes.  It doesn't appear the scroll eventHandler on the window object is debounced or throttled.

Debouncing it through the console via the following method relieves some of the jankiness.


{code:javascript}
function debounce(fn, delay) {
	var timer = null;
	return function () {
		var context = this, args = arguments;
		clearTimeout(timer);
		timer = setTimeout(function () {
			fn.apply(context, args);
		}, delay);
	};
}
getEventListeners(window).scroll.forEach(function(f) {
	var l = f.listener;
	f.remove();
	window.addEventListener('scroll', debounce(l, 25));
});{code}

